snippet.textDisplay:
i counted the pixels a bit... - based on an guess of the disk-slot being 12.5cm (standard size for slot-in drives)
the physical size of this thin should be about 30x16x16cm (11.8x6.3x6.3 inches) including the feet which is about 7.5l for internal volume. for comparison the Dancase A4 has 7.2l internal volume.
so basically they building a ultra small form factor pc.
as the cpu und gpu are probably on a single substrate, you win space from the GPU, but you'll also have to factor in the optical drive (a slimline optical drive is not that bad, and judging by the location of the disk-slot, it probably is one). this leaves easily space for proper air cooling with a reasonable sized heatsink for the SoC.
I'm also guessing they have airflow from bottom to top (like the corsair one) - hopefully they have some dust shields at the bottom intake
the main downside for this format is, that you probably want it standing rather than lying...
will not buy one, pcmr all the way ;)

snippet.textDisplay:
It's disheartening to see, with every generation launch announcement, a group of people saying that >insert console name< is as powerful, if not more, than a PC of the same price, therefore, >insert joke about PC Master Race< or some variation of that.

Is it just trolling and people having fun, or are those people genuinely unaware that consoles will never be as powerful as a PC of the same price, no matter how bleeding-edge the technology is when announced? I thought, by now, it was common knowledge that console hardware is fixed, while on a PC it's not, and that means all the hardware announced NOW will be old news when the console actually gets released (and said console will not drop in price anytime soon, btw). Meanwhile, people buying a PC on the exact same date of launch, will either buy a more powerful PC for the same price, or a similar spec PC for less money than the console. It's always been like this, and will continue to be so.

Adding insult to injury, multiplayer on PC is mostly free, while Consoles all ask for a yearly subscription. And PC games tend to cheaper too. Bottom-line is, why the silly comparisons, literally every generation? Consoles exist for people who are willing to pay more for simplicity - throw a disc in, install, and play. People who don't mind a bit of complexity (knowing what a driver is, for example) will always find a PC to be cheaper and/or a better deal. Why do you think the companies make such a big deal about ''exclusive'' titles? Because without them, there would be hardly anyone opting for a console. This is not something of this or that generation, it's a universal characteristic of the industry.
